The Egyptian government said today that Iraqi agents or Egyptian
Moslem fundamentalists were responsible for the assassination Friday
of Rifaat el- Mahgoub, its second-highest official. The Interior
Minister said saboteurs with orders from Iraqi President Sadam Hussein
had been sent to assassinate Egyptian officials. This was the first
assassination of an Egyptian politician since President Anwar Sadat
was killed by Islamic extremists nine years ago. The newspaper
Al-Ahram reported that Moslem extremists were collaborating with
Palestinian terrorists sent by Iraq and that El-Mahgoub was
assassinated to tell the terrorists' bosses that they had pierced the
stability of Egypt.</SUM>

