A joint military-prosecution investigation team which probed the
assassination of South Korean President Pak Chong-hui by then Central
Intelligence Agency Director Kim Chae-kyu in October 1979 found no
evidence that then Army Chief of Staff and martial law commander,
Gen. Chong Sung-hwa was an accomplice in the crime. Chong was nearby
when Kim killed Pak and was subsequently arrested and indicted on a
charge of high treason despite a lack of concrete evidence. The Seoul
District Prosecutor's Office is looking into a criminal suit filed by
victims of the Dec. 12, 1979 arrests including Chong.</SUM>
